      <hedline>
        <hl1>Dental Care for the Poor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elizabeth Price letter, commenting on May 26 article, says US should ensure dental care for all its children</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '' 'Epidemic of Oral Disease' Is Found in Poor'' (news article, May 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '' 'Epidemic of Oral Disease' Is Found in Poor'' (news article, May 26):</p>
        <p>As a recent medical school graduate, I was heartened to hear about the much-needed attention that Dr. David Satcher, the surgeon general, is paying to this important issue.  During my clinical rotations I encountered patients, both children and adults, in need of basic dental services.</p>
        <p>Too often, access to such services is limited by socioeconomic factors.  Families without insurance often simply cannot pay for dental visits.  But regular preventive measures  will save these patients from extensive, expensive and possibly painful dental repairs years later.</p>
        <p>It is unconscionable that any child in this wealthy country should grow up without yearly dental checkups, which can also provide essential information on how to brush and floss properly.</p>
        <p>ELIZABETH PRICE, M.D.  Somerville, Mass., May 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
